 Amory  , and 2 below.","French: from the Old French personal name <i>Aimery</i>, ancient Germanic <i>Haimeric</i>, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’+ <i>rīc</i> ‘power(ful)’. This may occasionally also be a derivation of the English surname (see 1 above). Compare   Lemery  .","Americanized form of German   Hemmerich  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Emory","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Emery  . This form of the surname has now died out in Britain."]},{"name":"Amery","meanings":["English (of Norman origin):","from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Amalric</i>, composed of the elements <i>Amal</i> (a dynastic name among the Goths) + <i>rīk</i> ‘realm, power’. The name was introduced into England from France by the Normans, developing into the Middle English personal name <i>Amery</i>, <i>Emery</i> (from Old French <i>Amauri</i>, <i>Emaurri</i>).","occasionally perhaps also from the Middle English, Old French personal name <i>Aimery</i>, ancient Germanic <i>Haimeric</i>, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’+ <i>rīc</i> ‘power(ful)’. Compare   Emery  ."]},{"name":"Amory","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Emery  , a cognate of 3 below.","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Daumeray in Maine-et-Loire, France, introduced to England by the Normans. The initial <i>D-</i> was often regarded as a preposition and the name wrongly divided as <i>De Aumari</i>. This false preposition was later lost, hence <i>Amori</i>, <i>Amory</i>. The name was probably then confused with   Amery  .","French: from the Old French personal name <i>Amauri</i>, from ancient Germanic <i>Amalric</i>, composed of the elements <i>Amal</i> (a dynastic name among the Goths) + <i>rīk</i> ‘realm, power’."]},{"name":"Embry","meanings":["English: habitational name either from Emborough (Somerset), any of the three places called Hembury (Devon), or any of three place called Henbury (Gloucestershire, Cheshire, Dorset). Emborough is from Old English <i>emn</i> ‘flat-topped’ + <i>beorg</i> ‘mound or hill’, while Henbury in Gloucestershire comes from Old English <i>hēah</i> ‘high’ + <i>burh</i> (dative <i>byrig</i>) ‘fortified place’. Henbury in Chesire has an uncertain first element, possibly Old English <i>hæmed</i> ‘community’.","English (of Norman origin): variant of   Emery   1."]},{"name":"Emry","meanings":["Altered form of   Emery  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":1,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705197,"age":74,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the 